
<!doctype linuxdoc system>

<manpage TITLE="camelot" SECTNUM=8>
<sect1>NAME 
 <P>camelot - Camelot transaction system



<sect1>SYNOPSIS<P>
camelot &lsqb;-backup&rsqb; &lsqb;-backupFile&rsqb; &lsqb;-config&rsqb; &lsqb;-file&rsqb; &lsqb;-init&rsqb; &lsqb;-other&rsqb; &lsqb;-path&rsqb;<P>
&lsqb;-print&rsqb; &lsqb;-restart&rsqb; &lsqb;-restore&rsqb; &lsqb;-tail&rsqb; &lsqb;-v&rsqb;<P>


<sect1>DESCRIPTION<P>

<bf>Camelot</bf> is the start-up program for the Camelot transaction facility. <bf>Camelot</bf>
reads a configuration file to determine the options and starts the various
camelot tasks. <bf>Camelot</bf> can also be set to automatically restart the camelot
tasks after crashes. Switches to camelot include:

<sect1>DESCRIPTION<P>
<descrip>
<tag><bf>-backup</bf></tag> Backup the Camelot Log and Data.
<P></descrip>

<descrip>
<tag><bf>-backupFile</bf></tag> Ask for a file to backup the Camelot Log 
and Data.
<P></descrip>

<descrip>
<tag><bf>-config</bf></tag> Cause <bf>Camelot</bf> to start an interactive 
session to set up the Camelot configuration file. This session is also started 
if <bf>Camelot</bf> cannot find the configuration file (as in the first time
<bf>Camelot</bf> is run).
<P></descrip>

<descrip>
<tag><bf>-file</bf></tag> Specify the configuration file.
<P></descrip>

<descrip>
<tag><bf>-init</bf></tag> Initialize the paging and logging areas. 
<bf>Camelot</bf> will ask the user to confirm this option. Initializing the
logger causes camelot to zero-fill the logging area, a potentially slow
operation.  Initializing the pager causes a tombstone record to be written 
to the log, a far less time-consuming operation. The Camelot manual suggests
only initializing the paging areas for large systems.
<P></descrip>

<descrip>
<tag><bf>-other</bf></tag> Supply the arguments to the Camelot modules.
<P></descrip>

<descrip>
<tag><bf>-path</bf></tag> Supply the pathnames of the Camelot modules.
<P></descrip>

<descrip>
<tag><bf>-print</bf></tag> Print the start-up messages, do NOT run Camelot.
<P></descrip>

<descrip>
<tag><bf>-restart</bf></tag> Restart Camelot, should it die.
<P></descrip>

<descrip>
<tag><bf>-restore</bf></tag> Restore the Camelot Log and Data.
<P></descrip>

<descrip>
<tag><bf>-tail</bf></tag> Tail the camelot log to the current STDOUT.
<P></descrip>

<descrip>
<tag><bf>-v</bf></tag> Print the version number of this version of Camelot.
<P></descrip>


For a more detailed list of the arguments, run camelot with the -bogus flag.

The <bf>Camelot</bf> program does not need to be run in the background unless the
<em>-restart</em> flag is given. It should be run in the foreground if started with
the <em>-config</em> or <em>-init</em> switches since it will try to interact with the user.
              

<sect1>Files<P>
<em>/usr/camelot/CAMELOT&lowbar;CONFIGURATION</em>,

<em>/usr/camelot/bin/diskllog</em>,

<em>/usr/camelot/bin/recllog</em>,

<em>/usr/camelot/bin/trancom</em>,

<em>/usr/camelot/bin/mcp</em>,

<em>/usr/camelot/bin/com</em>.  



